{"title":"Spatial Reasoning from Natural Language Instructions for Robot Manipulation","domain":"ROBOTICS","seeds":[{"problem":"Grounding natural-language spatial instructions into precise pick-and-place coordinates generalizes poorly when scene object positions are fed as unordered coordinate lists and processed with fully connected layers, which overfit to absolute locations and fail to capture spatial patterns (e.g., rows).","method":"Adopt a two-stage pipeline: (1) detect and localize objects, then quantize detections into a binary 2D grid with one-hot channels per object type plus a size map; (2) condition on the instruction by correlating learned instruction embeddings with the object grid to form spatial ‘soft-selections’, and pass these through a convolutional hourglass U-Net to produce start/end heatmaps from which coordinates are extracted via spatial softmax. The convolutional, translation-invariant grid representation enables robust spatial reasoning (e.g., recognizing rows) and eliminates hard-coded offsets, outperforming list+FC and end-to-end baselines (e.g., on the synthetic set: TA 95.99% vs 59.88% for Lang-FCNet and 44.89% for LSTM+CNN+SA)."},{"problem":"Biased datasets can cause language-only or non-attentive models to memorize spurious associations between object IDs and offsets (e.g., certain blocks often ‘above’), hurting generalization, especially for predicting end targets.","method":"Introduce multi-head attention over a BiLSTM instruction encoder with four heads: two heads project to select start/anchor objects via correlation with the object map; two capture spatial-relation attributes (offset/direction) and are concatenated with visual features before the U-Net. This attention forces the model to focus on the correct tokens (e.g., the offset word), improving end-coordinate prediction and mitigating bias (e.g., after randomizing block numbers, attention-based models retain 19/20 correct vs 6/20 for a no-attention baseline)."},{"problem":"End-to-end vision–language models must jointly learn detection and grounding from limited data, which degrades instruction-following performance in manipulation tasks.","method":"Use a pipelined architecture separating perception (a fine-tuned object detector, e.g., SSD) from language-conditioned spatial grounding (the above grid+U-Net model). Empirically, pipelined models (Lang-UNet/Lang-FCNet) outperform end-to-end LSTM+CNN(+SA) across Blocks and a more diverse synthetic dataset. The full system executes on a real Dobot arm, picking the correct card in all 15 trials and placing within 1 cm in 14/15 cases."}]}
